Citation.sAbstract: Molar excess volumes, VE, molar excess enthalpies, HE, and speeds of sound data, u, of chloroform  (i) + aniline or o-toluidine (j) binary mixtures have been measured as a function of composition at 308.15 K.  Isentropic compressibility changes of mixing,  E  S have been determined by employing speed of sound data.  Topological investigations of VE data reveals that aniline, chloroform and o-toluidine are associated entities  and these (i + j) mixtures contain a 1:1 molecular complex. The IR studies lend further support to the  nature and extent of interaction for the proposed molecular entity in the mixtures. HE and  E  S values have  also been calculated by employing Moelwyn-Huggins concept [Polymer 12 (1971) 387] taking topology  of the constituents of the mixtures. It has been observed that calculated HE and  E  S values compare well  with their corresponding experimental values. The observed VE, HE and  E  S data have also been analyzed  in terms of Flory theory.
Citation.sTitle: Topological and thermodynamic investigations of molecular interactions of aniline and o-toluidine with chloroform
